Author-Workplace-Name: Charles H. Lundquist College of Business, University of Oregon 
Author-Name: Jarrad Harford 
Author-Workplace-Name: Charles H. Lundquist College of Business, University of Oregon 
Title: Managerial Opportunism? Evidence from Directors' and Officers' Insurance Purchases 
Abstract:
 We analyze a sample of 72 IPO firms that went public between 1992 and 1996
 for which we have detailed proprietary information about the amount and
 cost of D&O liability insurance. If managers of IPO firms are exploiting
 superior inside information, we hypothesize that the amount of insurance
 coverage chosen will be related to the post-offering performance of the
 issuing firm's shares. Consistent with the hypothesis, we find a
 significant negative relation between the three-year post-IPO stock price
 performance and the insurance coverage purchased in conjunction with the
 IPO. One plausible interpretation is that, like insider securities
 transactions, D&O insurance decisions reveal opportunistic behavior by
 managers. This provides some motivation to argue that disclosure of the
 details of D&O insurance decisions, as is required in some other
 countries, is valuable. Copyright The American Finance Association 2002. 
