Title: The Volatility and Price Sensitivities of Managerial Stock Option Portfolios and Corporate Hedging 
Abstract:
 We use estimates of the Black-Scholes sensitivity of managers' stock
 option portfolios to stock return volatility and the sensitivity of
 managers' stock and stock option portfolios to stock price to test the
 relationship between managers' risk preferences and hedging activities. We
 find that as the sensitivity of managers' stock and stock option
 portfolios to stock price increases, firms tend to hedge more. However, as
 the sensitivity of managers' stock option portfolios to stock return
 volatility increases, firms tend to hedge less. Copyright The American Finance Association 2002. 
