Title: Do Firms Hedge in Response to Tax Incentives? 
Abstract:
 There are two tax incentives for corporations to hedge: to increase debt
 capacity and interest tax deductions, and to reduce expected tax liability
 if the tax function is convex. We test whether these incentives affect the
 extent of corporate hedging with derivatives. Using an explicit measure of
 tax function convexity, we find no evidence that firms hedge in response
 to tax convexity. Our analysis does, however, indicate that firms hedge to
 increase debt capacity, with increased tax benefits averaging 1.1 percent
 of firm value. Our results also indicate that firms hedge because of
 expected financial distress costs and firm size. Copyright The American Finance Association 2002. 
