Title: Liquidity Provision and the Organizational Form of NYSE Specialist Firms 
Abstract:
 We examine the influence of NYSE specialist firm organizational form on
 the nature of liquidity provision. We compare closely held firms whose
 specialists provide liquidity with their own capital to widely held firms
 whose specialists provide liquidity with diffusely owned capital. We argue
 that specialists using their own capital have a greater incentive and
 ability to reduce adverse selection costs, but face a greater cost of
 capital. Differences in the proportion of spreads due to adverse selection
 costs, large trade frequency, the sensitivity between depth and spreads,
 and price stabilization support this argument. Copyright The American Finance Association 2002. 
